// ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
// STEP-BY-STEP CLASSIFICATION PROCEDURE
// ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

// 1. NAVIGATE TO THE LOCATION
//    - Open the provided KMZ file in Google Earth Pro.
//    - Double-click on a polygon in the 'Places' sidebar to check its ID and 
//      navigate automatically to its location.

// 2. CONFIRM AGRICULTURAL LAND USE
//    - Confirm if the polygon is on agricultural land. 
//    - If it is agricultural land, move to Step 3. 
//    - Otherwise, assign it one of the following values in the Excel sheet and move on:
//        >>> 0 : Not agricultural land (e.g., urban, bare soil, desert).
//        >>> 5 : Overlapping (Only 30% or less of the polygon area overlaps 
//                agricultural land; the rest is infrastructure/buildings).
//        >>> 6 : Trees (Forest or tree crops/orchards).

// 3. ESTABLISH TEMPORAL CONTEXT
//    - Click the 'Historical Imagery' clock icon in the top toolbar.
//    - Make sure it is on the year of interest (start with the most recent year).
//    - Pay close attention to which month you are looking at.

// 4. EVALUATE SPATIAL CONTEXT & FORM A HYPOTHESIS
//    - Check the polygon location within the agricultural field.
//    - Check the surrounding fields.
//    - Look for the existence of irrigation infrastructure and the location's 
//      proximity to it.

// 5. MAKE AN EDUCATED GUESS
//    Make an educated guess based on:
//    a. The location information above (proximity to irrigation infrastructure, 
//       texture contrast among neighboring fields).
//    b. Water reservoirs (See 'Clues' section below).
//    c. The greenness in the year and month appearing in the Very High Resolution (VHR) 
//       satellite images. (Sometimes more than one image is available per year; 
//       check all photos from different months).
//    d. The level of management (tillage/plowing), planting patterns, and texture 
//       you can observe in the VHR imagery.
//
//    WHAT TO LOOK FOR:
//    - High greenness in Summer >> Highly likely irrigated.
//    - High greenness in Winter/Spring, but not in Summer >> Likely rainfed 
//      (Check other clues to verify).

// 6. CONFIRM YOUR GUESS AND ASSIGN A VALUE
//    - Check the corresponding ID in the Excel sheet and locate the polygon/year. 
//    - Check the NDVI value provided in the Excel sheet to confirm your decision. 
//      (This is the 95th percentile NDVI for June-July of that year).
//    - Once you make a decision, OVERWRITE the NDVI value using one of the following:
//        >>> 1 : Rainfed
//        >>> 2 : Irrigated, but not completely sure (Low Confidence)
//        >>> 3 : Irrigated (High Confidence)
//        >>> 4 : I can't tell (VHR is poor, cloudy, or ambiguous)
//        >>> 0, 5, 6 : (See non-agricultural codes in Step 2)

// 7. CHECK PREVIOUS YEARS
//    - Move the history bar in Google Earth to the previous available year 
//      and repeat from Step 4.

// 8. SKIP UNAVAILABLE YEARS
//    - Skip the years where VHR is unavailable. 
//    - Once all years with VHR images for the current ID are completed, 
//      move to the next polygon.


